\begin_layout Title
Corporate Finance - Lecture 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Leonid Genkin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This course is a natural continuation of Finance I and Finance II.
 Several cases will be presented and anlyzed in class, on various topics:
 bankruptcy, private equity, takeovers and startup financing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bankruptcy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall from Finance II: bankruptcy has costs (legal, auditors, administrative,
 indirect expenses, etc).
 Therefore sometimes it can be inefficient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bankruptcy is not something one 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

likes to talk about
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, yet it is very important.
 Talking about it implies determining the value of the company.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Understanding the value drivers of a company and the negotiation forces
 in a bankruptcy affect its costs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a company files for bankruptcy, interest conflicts between debt holders
 and equity holders might arise, regrading the firm's value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Capital Structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There might be a difference between the book and the market value of a firm's
 assets (especially in times of distress).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Accounting B/S: Assets = Liabilities + Equity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current liabilities are usually those <1 year.
 The most imoportant ones are: A/P, taxes, accrued expenses; debt, capital
 leases, pension and other accrued expenses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Debt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Lines of credit
\series default
 is the maximum amount the bank is willing to lend to the firm (instead
 of issuing debt each time money is needed).
 In a 
\series bold
revolver
\series default
, the bank is obligated to keep lending after the firm repays back.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\series bold
indenture
\series default
 is a debt contract will all the details (interest, schedule, seniority,
 covenants).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Seniority
\series default
: Defines the priority in case of bankruptcy.
 Bank loans are usually senior debt, while issued bonds are more junior.
 Banks look at the B/S and the existing debts of a firm before lending to
 it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Collateral
\series default
: If the debt cannot be repaid, an ownership over assets can be taken in
 some cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Covenants
\series default
: Limitations on the actions a firm can take (debt ratios, interest coverage
 ratio, management provision, assets selling off, dividends payment, etc).
 Can be negative / positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Callable features
\series default
: Any bond can be bought back.
 The callability implies prepayment and the difference is that there is
 a predetermined price in the latter case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
syndicated loans
\series default
 is one that is provided by several banks.
 A lead bank arranges other creditors for a fee and manages the negotiations
 (interest & principal) - participants are not involved.
 The rational for such loans is risk spreading.
 For example, small banks might have too much money on their B/S.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Israel the bond market is more sophisticated than in the U.S - they can
 be traded on the stock exchange, unlike the U.S where they can only be initially
 bought over the counter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A direct long-term loan avoids the SEC registrationg cost and is likely
 to have more restrictive covenants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Collaterals (a.k.a 
\series bold
lien
\series default
) can be a firm's assets, stocks/bonds (risky) , receivables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even when covenants are violated, banks usually try to renegotiate the terms
 (forcing the company to default will probably make them worse off).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A
\series bold
 lease
\series default
 requires the user to pay the owner for the use of an asset.
 In a 
\series bold
capital lease
\series default
, the lessor only finances the lease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Balance Sheet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to always remember the important identity of 
\begin_inset Formula $A=L+E$
\end_inset

 which is both an economic and a financial identity, when analyzing a firm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The accounting B/S represents the economic value of assets in place, without
 the future growth opportunities (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what you owe
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 The economic B/S incorporates the future cash flows projections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Creditors tend to dislike assets sells, as they may transfer value from
 them to equity holders (consider an example with 50%-50% low-high outcome,
 and the bad outcome might or might not make the firm unable to fully repay
 its debt).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible that even when the value of the firm is larger than the debt,
 it is still traded at a discount - caused by volatility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Financial Distress
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
financial distress
\series default
 occurs when a firm's operating CF are insufficient to satisfy its current
 obligations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\series bold
insolvency
\series default
 is a situation when the value of a firm's assets is lower than its obligations
 (debt).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
flow-base insolvency
\series default
 happens when a firm's cash flows are insufficient for it to pay its contractual
ly required payments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Possible solutions to financial distress include: asset restructuring (selling,
 merging, costs cutting) or financial restructuring (terms negotiation,
 long-term financing, bankruptcy).
 The first priority is to ensure the maximum economic value of the assets,
 while satisfying creditors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Financial restructuring happens in about half of the cases of a financial
 distress, out of them about half results in private workout (might be taxable
 - capital gain) and another half leads to legal bankruptcy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bankruptcy chapter 11 - workout; chapter 7 - liquidations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bankruptcy Procedure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The procedures vary across different countries.
 It is related to the role of equity holders, the ability of the management
 to come up with a plan, the ability of the debt holders to take over the
 collateral.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the U.S the bankruptcy procedures tend to protect the shareholders, while
 in Europe they are more friendly for the debt holders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Liquidation (Chapter 7)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A petition is filed in a federal court.
 It may be initiated by the firm (voluntary) or its creditors (involuntary).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A trustee (usually a lawyer) is appointed by the judge, who will attempt
 to liquidate the assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
After selling the assets and paying the administration costs, it is redistribute
d to the creditors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If any money is left - the shareholders get it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reorganization (Chapter 11)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A (voluntary or involuntary) petition is filed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The judge approves or denies it (the economic goal is to figure out 
\series bold
the highest value
\series default
, otherwise it will be dismissed).
 A senior creditor will usually prefer chapter 7, as it provides him an
 easier solution to get his money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The firm usually continues to run the business (in the UK the management
 has to be replaced).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A reorganization plan must be submitted within 120 days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
1/3 of creditors who own 2/3 of the outstanding debt 
\series bold
in each class 
\series default
have to approve the plan.
 The creditors are divided to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
After creditors acceptance, the plan is confirmed by the court.
 Even though all the creditors are required to vote on the plan and may
 vote against it, the judge can overrule them (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

would the value be more in case of liquidation?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Payments are made in cash, property and securities to the creditors and
 shareholders.
 The judge need to solve disputes regarding the true value of assets.
\end_layout

